{"schema_version": 2, "source_hash": "4baf10ae7adfff36", "candidate": {"id": "cand-009", "name": "Raj Mehta", "raw_cv": "RAJ MEHTA\nraj.mehta@email.com | London, UK\n\nSENIOR DATA ENGINEER\n\nPROFESSIONAL SUMMARY\nData engineer with 5 years of experience in fintech data platforms, specialising in Python, dbt, and real-time data pipelines. Strong SQL skills and experience with Snowflake and Airflow.\n\nEXPERIENCE\n\nSenior Data Engineer \u2014 Starling Bank, London (2020\u2013present)\n- Built and maintained the bank's core financial data pipelines using Python and dbt on Snowflake\n- Designed Airflow orchestration for 60+ daily reconciliation and reporting jobs\n- Led implementation of data quality framework using Great Expectations\n- Worked with compliance team on CASS data reporting requirements\n\nData Engineer \u2014 TransferWise (now Wise), London (2019\u20132020)\n- Developed real-time FX data pipelines feeding pricing models\n- Built internal analytics models in BigQuery\n\nSKILLS\nPython, SQL, dbt, Snowflake, BigQuery, Airflow, Great Expectations, Kafka (consumer), Docker\n\nEDUCATION\nBSc Computer Science \u2014 King's College London (2016\u20132019)\n\nVISA STATUS\nIndian national, currently on Tier 2 Skilled Worker visa (sponsored by Starling Bank)", "raw_linkedin": "Data engineer in London fintech \u2014 currently at Starling Bank building the data infrastructure that helps the operations and compliance teams sleep at night. Strong background in Python, dbt, and Snowflake. Five years of experience across digital banking and payments. Interested in fintech data engineering roles. UK-based on a Skilled Worker visa.\n\nNote: My current visa is sponsored by Starling Bank. I am actively exploring my options given upcoming changes at my employer. Visa transfer to a new employer is straightforward for Skilled Worker roles, but I do require the new employer to act as a sponsor.", "raw_interview_transcript": "Interviewer: Raj, thanks for coming in today. Walk me through your experience at Starling.\n\nRaj: I've been at Starling for four years now. I joined as a data engineer and I've grown into a senior role leading a pod of three engineers. My main area is financial data pipelines \u2014 the stuff that feeds reconciliation, CASS reporting, and the finance team's dashboards. It's a high-stakes environment because the numbers feed regulatory submissions.\n\nInterviewer: Your profile looks excellent. I do need to ask about your visa situation \u2014 we saw a note on your LinkedIn. We do not offer visa sponsorship.\n\nRaj: I understand. I'm currently on a Skilled Worker visa sponsored by Starling. To work for a new employer, I would need the new employer to be an approved UK Visas and Immigration sponsor and to sponsor the transfer. It's not a new visa application \u2014 it's a transfer \u2014 but it does require the employer to hold a sponsor licence.\n\nInterviewer: I see. Unfortunately Apex doesn't currently hold a sponsor licence, and we have a policy of hiring candidates who have the right to work without sponsorship requirements. That would create a barrier here.\n\nRaj: I appreciate you being clear about that. I was hoping it might not be an issue given it's a transfer rather than a new application, but I understand the position. Is there any possibility of the company obtaining a licence?\n\nInterviewer: It's not something we're in a position to pursue at this stage. I'm sorry \u2014 your technical background is genuinely impressive.", "years_experience": 5.0, "skills": ["Python", "SQL", "dbt", "Snowflake", "BigQuery", "Airflow", "Great Expectations", "Kafka", "Docker", "Data pipelines", "Real-time data processing", "Financial data systems", "Data quality frameworks"], "industries": ["fintech", "digital banking", "payments"], "seniority_level": "senior", "management_experience": true, "education_level": "bachelor", "career_trajectory": "ascending", "interview_score": 0.88, "culture_fit_score": 0.85, "constraints": [{"